15. Shift4 incorrectly alleges that Card Connect "secretly developed a plan ... to
exploit a loophole in the Agreement .. ." (Motion, p. 7.) Shift4 points to a presentation deck I
prepared, entitled "Project Galaxy" (Exhibit 6 to Shift4's Motion), and falsely suggests that it proves
some nefarious scheme to raid Shift4' s customers. That is absolutely incorrect.
16. Card Connect recognized significant dissatisfaction among shared customers
who wanted assistance from Card Connect to use a different payment processor.
17. Project Galaxy was created to develop a straightforward method to pennit a select
group of large, sophisticated merchants (who were also being serviced by Card Connect for their
payment processing) to switch to a new payment processor if they so chose, and allow Card Connect to
facilitate that switch. The method set forth in the Project Galaxy deck was consistent with Card
Connect's obligations under the Agreement. At its core, Card Connect recognized that merchants,
including those working with Shift4 and using its payment gateway, had the right to choose their
own payment processor, and that Card Connect was contractually permitted to assist them in
switching processors, if they so chose.

```
AND NOW, this 6th day of March, 2019, upon consideration of Defendant’s
Motion for Sanctions for Spoliation of Evidence (ECF No. 97), and the briefs and exhibits
submitted by the parties in support thereof and in opposition thereto, IT IS HEREBY
ORDERED that Defendant’s Motion for Sanctions is GRANTED IN PART and DENIED IN
PART.
IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that:
         1. Defendant’s request for sanctions based on Plaintiff’s alleged spoliation of
         evidence is GRANTED as follows:
                 a. An adverse inference instruction shall be given to the jury regarding the
                 text messages that Plaintiff failed to preserve.
```
